Woods reeled off three-straight top-15 fantasy campaigns during 2018-20 and was lower than 13th among wide receivers in snaps, routes, targets and receptions during each campaign. He was on his way to another solid year in 2021 (16th in fantasy PPG despite a slow start), but a torn ACL ended his season after nine games. Woods is past his prime at age-30, not much of a TD scorer (career-high is six TDs) and is now moving to one of the league's run-heaviest offenses. He's expected to be a full go for Week 1, but even as the Titans' No. 1 wideout, he'll likely be limited to the WR3/flex radar with a limited ceiling.

Statistically speaking, Claypool's first two NFL seasons were almost identical in every category with one major exception: touchdowns. He found the end zone on nine of 107 targets (8.4% TD rate) as a rookie, but scored on just two of 104 targets (1.9%) in 2021. The 2020 second-round pick's reception total, yardage, catch rate, off-target rate, yards per reception, yards per target and even his end zone targets (seven in 2020, eight in 2021) were about the same both seasons, but the scoring dip dropped him from 23rd to 37th in fantasy points at WR. Ben Roethlisberger's late-career falloff was an obvious culprit and, though the Steelers' QB situation remains shaky, Claypool is still on the rise at age 23 and has great size at 6-foot-4, 238 pounds. Especially with JuJu Smith-Schuster gone, Claypool is, at worst, a flex.

Gay has been a fantasy star since entering the league in 2019. He was the No. 4 fantasy kicker with Tampa Bay as a rookie before posting the sixth-most points during a seven-game stint with the Rams in 2020. Gay followed with a fifth-place fantasy campaign in 2021. The 2019 fifth-round pick struggled with accuracy as a rookie, but not so much since that point. Last season, Gay nailed 32-of-34 field goals during the regular season and his 94.1% conversion rate trailed only Justin Tucker for best in the league. He has missed just one of 65 extra-point attempts over the last two seasons. Kicking for one of the league's top teams, the 28-year-old is positioned for another strong fantasy campaign.

Toney had quite the polarizing rookie season, showing flashes of heavy usage and playmaking ability, but also suffering badly due to multiple injuries and the Giants' dreadful offense. Toney's high point came in a Week 5 game in which he racked up 189 yards, the seventh-most by a rookie in a single game during the last 20 seasons. Toney didn't see much goal-line work (zero TDs, two end zone targets) and was primarily used in the short area (6.4 aDOT), though he made up a ton of ground with the ball in his hands (6.0 RAC ranked 10th). Durability and New York's QB situation are concerns, but Toney has elite playmaking ability and a new coach in Brian Daboll. Target him as a flex with major breakout potential.

Carr posted career-high marks in pass attempts, completions and yards last season, finishing top five in all three categories. And yet he still failed to post his first ever top-10 fantasy campaign. The primary culprit: A lack of rushing production. Carr has never cleared 140 rush yards in a single season and has six rushing TDs in eight campaigns. That will continue to limit Carr's fantasy output, but the good news is that he enters 2022 with the best supporting cast of his career after Las Vegas acquired Davante Adams as a running mate for Darren Waller, Hunter Renfrow and Josh Jacobs. Carr should be considered a strong QB2 with back-end QB1 upside.

Kmet is entering his third NFL season after a bizarre 2021 campaign in which he was a featured target, but simply couldn't find the end zone. Kmet finished second among tight ends in snaps, as well as no lower than 12th in routes, targets, receptions and yardage. He also saw six end zone targets (14th most), but somehow failed to score a single touchdown. As a result, Kmet ended up 20th in fantasy points, but bad luck was obviously a major culprit. The 2020 second-round pick is obviously a full-time player and he's in an even better spot this season as QB Justin Fields enters his second season. Kmet is a breakout candidate in his age-23 campaign and a fine TE2 target.

After beginning his career with three consecutive top-seven fantasy campaigns, Butker has finished just outside the top 10 each of the last two seasons. That includes a career-worst 12th in 2021. A change in opportunity has been the issue, as the Chiefs ranked third in field goal attempts during the 2017-19 seasons, but 22nd the last two seasons. Butker's 2021 FG conversion rate of 89.3% was the second-lowest of his career, but when you factor in his career average distance (41.1), it was actually his most-accurate season. Despite the dip in field goal tries, the 27-year-old remains a terrific fantasy kicker due to his elite accuracy and Kansas City's high-scoring offense.

Gordon re-signed with Denver after a successful 2021 with the team. The veteran back is one of 11 players in NFL history with at least nine TDs in six straight seasons and one of 11 players in NFL history with zero TDs on 200-plus touches in a single season. How's that for an incredible stat? Gordon has found the end zone 67 times over the last six seasons after going scoreless as a rookie in 2015. He split backfield duties with Javonte Williams in Denver last season and posted a career-best 2.2 YAC, which was in the 80th percentile among backs. Despite the impressive season, Gordon hasn't had a top-12 fantasy campaign since 2018 and is now 29 years old. He's a strong bet to defer more work to Williams and figures to cap out as a pedestrian flex option, though he does have elite insurance value.

The Patriots made waves by signing both Henry and Jonnu Smith last offseason, but it didn't take long for the former to emerge as the clear leader of the group. Granted, he wasn't targeted a ton (19th at the position), but Henry was very busy near the goal line, ranking first in touchdowns (nine), third in expected TDs (7.7) and second in end zone targets (12). Henry ended up 10th in fantasy points, marking his third consecutive top-12 fantasy campaign. He did see a late-season boost in targets and, coupled with his heavy goal-line usage and Mac Jones' strong play, the 27-year-old tight end is very much in the TE1 discussion.

Injuries ravaged the Ravens more so than any other team last season and it showed up in its D/ST output. Baltimore finished 27th in fantasy points after five consecutive seasons as a top-seven unit. Prior to 2021, Baltimore had finished no worse than 12th in yards allowed in an incredible eight consecutive seasons. Now healthy, the Ravens once again have a top secondary, which is led by Marlon Humphrey, Marcus Peters (who missed all of 2021), Chuck Clark, prize free-agent addition Marcus Williams and first-round rookie Kyle Hamilton. Add that group to the likes of Calais Campbell, Michael Pierce and 2021 first-round pick Odafe Oweh and suddenly this has the look of a top-10 overall unit on paper. Baltimore is well positioned for a major rebound and is a viable starting option in fantasy.

Wilson was selected by the Jets with the 10th overall pick of April's draft. The Ohio State product is a quick and elusive prospect who primarily worked as a perimeter receiver and punt returner at OSU. Wilson has terrific hands, having dropped only six balls during his college career and posting a strong 90% catch rate on on-target throws in 2021. That 2021 campaign included a terrific 70-1058-12 receiving line in 11 games. Wilson figures to immediately slide in as a starter opposite second-year Elijah Moore, with Corey Davis and Braxton Berrios also in the fold. Wilson has more competition for targets than many of his fellow rookies, but history tells us top-10 rookie WRs are a strong bet to see big volume and provide weekly WR3/flex production.

The 49ers' D/ST finished seventh in fantasy points last season. That followed a third-place finish in 2019 and a 13th-place campaign during an injury-riddled 2020. The 49ers have ranked no worse than fifth in yards allowed each of the last three seasons and they ranked first in forced fumbles, fifth in sacks and top 10 in points allowed in both 2019 and 2021. Interceptions have been an issue (nine in 2021), but this is a very good defense on paper, led by stars Nick Bosa, Fred Warner, Jimmie Ward and Arik Armstead.  Several regulars departed during the offseason, but they were replaced by players returning from injury, as well as free-agent signings Kerry Hyder, Kemoko Turay and -- most importantly -- new top corner Charvarius Ward. This is a fine starting option in fantasy.

Robinson has been a fantasy force during his first two NFL seasons, but the 2020 UDFA now has more roadblocks than ever before to consistent production. Robinson tore his Achilles late in the 2021 season, which puts his early 2022 availability (and effectiveness) in doubt. Even if ready to play, Robinson will, at best, be sharing the backfield with 2021 first-round pick Travis Etienne Jr. Once healthy, the 220-pound Robinson figures to contribute primarily as a rusher (he owns a career 4.55 YPC), with Etienne the bigger factor in the passing game. Robinson is likely to cap out as a low-ceiling flex option in 2022, but his recovery will need to be monitored throughout the summer.

Valdes-Scantling landed $15 million guaranteed from the Chiefs after spending his first four seasons with Green Bay. It's a decent chunk for a player that has never finished a season higher than 50th in targets, receptions, yards or fantasy points among WRs despite playing with Aaron Rodgers. The 2018 fifth-round pick has taken "boom/bust vertical target" to the extreme, ranking first in average depth of target (15.8) and yards per reception (17.5), but last in catch rate (50.2%) and off-target rate (32%) since entering the league. The 27-year-old remains in an elite offense and has a path to an every-down role, but his lack of emergence in Green Bay is a red flag. He's worth only a late-round flier.

Cousins has proven to be the ultimate QB2 in recent years, having failed to post a top-10 fantasy campaign since 2017, but having also delivered six top-12 campaigns over the last seven seasons. Cousins does his damage with his arm, having finished no lower than ninth in passing TDs each of the last five seasons. He's also been top 10 in passing yards six of the last seven seasons. The Minnesota offense will look different with new coach Kevin O'Connell calling the shots, but that may actually lead to more passing volume for Cousins. The 34-year-old doesn't offer much with his legs (career high of 179 rush yards), but he's been playing at a high level for years and has Justin Jefferson, Adam Thielen and Dalvin Cook in his arsenal. Cousins is a strong QB2.

Carter is entering his second season with the Jets, though his fantasy value took a major hit when the team drafted Breece Hall in April. Carter -- a 2021 fourth-round pick -- shared backfield duties during most of his first season, but he showed his upside when called upon for a larger workload around midseason. Carter hit a high in Week 8 against the Bengals, pacing all backs in fantasy points thanks to 172 yards and a score on 24 touches. His playing time dwindled from there, however, and he missed three games due to injury. Carter impressed as a rookie and has upside as a receiver, but he's a bit undersized and is now likely to be limited to situational carries and a passing-down role behind Hall. Carter has some insurance appeal, but he figures to struggle for consistent flex production.

Cook was selected by Buffalo in the second round of April's draft. Cook isn't quite as big or strong as his older brother, Dalvin, but he has the speed (4.42 40-yard dash), explosiveness and receiving ability to make noise in the pros as a situational back. He totaled 230 carries during four seasons at Georgia (career-high 113 as a senior), but his efficiency was terrific, as he averaged 6.5 yards per carry and 9.4 yards per target while not dropping a single one of his 78 career targets. Cook may never come close to the volume his brother enjoys, but he's joining an elite Buffalo offense and has big upside as a receiving specialist. Expect him to step into No. 2/passing-down duties behind Devin Singletary early on. Consistent fantasy value is unlikely, but he'll be an interesting insurance option and is well worth a late-round pick.

Carlson is the reigning top-scoring fantasy kicker. In fact, if we include his third-place finish in 2020, Carlson has scored 22 more fantasy points than any other kicker over the last two seasons. The 2018 fifth-round pick's success has stemmed from a combination of heavy volume and great accuracy. Carlson has converted 73-of-78 field goals over the last two seasons. That 93.6% hit rate trails only Younghoe Koo for tops in the league during the span. He attempted three more FGs than any other kicker in 2021 after finishing sixth in attempts in 2020. Las Vegas' offense only figures to be better this season with Davante Adams on the roster, so Carlson remains a strong fantasy option in his age-27 campaign.

Boyd has emerged into one of the league's best and most-reliable slot receivers over the last four seasons, but Cincinnati's recent WR additions have taken a toll on his fantasy output. Boyd averaged 8.1 targets per game (22% team share) during the 2018-20 seasons, but in 18 games with both Ja'Marr Chase and Tee Higgins last season, Boyd averaged 5.3 per game (16% share). He finished 37th in fantasy PPG, his worst showing since 2017. Boyd is only 27 and a tremendously important and reliable player (zero drops last season), but he'll be a WR3/flex option only if Chase or Higgins misses time.

Gesicki was slapped with the franchise tag and will return for his fifth season in Miami. Gesicki is fresh off a 2021 season in which he posted career-high marks in targets, receptions and yardage en route to his second consecutive top-eight fantasy campaign. Gesicki's fantasy production would've looked even better if not for a huge dip in goal line work. The 2018 second-round pick racked up 11 TDs and 22 end zone targets during the 2019-20 seasons, but plummeted to four end zone targets (24th at TE) and two TDs (34th) in 2021. The 26-year-old has more competition for targets this season with Tyreek Hill in the mix, but a dip in targets can be offset by more scoring opportunities in what should be a better offense. Gesicki is a TE2.

The Dallas D/ST was the top-scoring fantasy unit in 2021, which ended a streak of 11 straight seasons finishing 14th or worse. The success was driven primarily by an enormous 26 INTs, which is the third most by a defense over the last decade, as well as 10 TDs, which was more than the nine the unit totaled the prior six seasons. Those two categories will regress and Dallas was otherwise around league average in most key categories, so a step back for this unit is likely. On the plus side, Dallas returns nearly its entire core and the biggest loss (Randy Gregory) was replaced by Dante Fowler Jr. and rookie Sam Williams. This defense has a few holes, but enough stars in DeMarcus Lawrence (who missed most of 2021), Micah Parsons and Trevon Diggs to generate another good fantasy campaign.

Walker was selected by Seattle in the second round of April's draft. Following a pair of ho-hum seasons at Wake Forest, Walker exploded for a 263-1636-18 rushing line in 12 games at Michigan State in 2021. He was extremely efficient, ranking third in this class in both YAC and FMT rate. Walker has a ways to go in the passing game (a 5% target share led to a 13-89-1 receiving line last season), but he's young (21) and sports a terrific speed/power combo (4.38 40-yard dash). Walker will open his career behind Rashaad Penny, but the latter's major durability concerns positions the rookie as an intriguing insurance stash. If Penny misses time, Walker would leap to the RB2 mix.

Hines has settled in as one of game's busiest passing-down specialists, having soaked up 274 targets and 282 carries during his four seasons in the league. Hines has flirted with occasional fantasy value (27th in 2018 and 15th in 2020), but the emergence of Jonathan Taylor crushed his value in 2021. Despite appearing in all 17 games, Hines posted career-low marks in routes, targets, receptions and receiving yards. His 5-foot-8 frame won't allow much usage as a rusher (career-high 89 carries) and, while the QB change to Matt Ryan could mean more targets, Indianapolis already targeted RBs at an above-average rate last season, so we can't count on much of a boost. The 25-year-old is best left on benches as long as Taylor is active.

Meyers has emerged as the Patriots' No. 1 wide receiver over the last two seasons, handling target shares of 23% and 24%. He's proven to be a reliable, short-range target, but historic struggles in the TD department have severely limited his fantasy output. Every WR in league history with at least 104 receptions has more than two TD catches  except Meyers, who has two on 168 receptions. Bad luck is part of the issue, but so is a lack of goal-line work (10 career end zone targets). Meyers' targets figure to dip this season with DeVante Parker (among others) added to the mix, so the 25-year-old is best viewed as a low-ceiling PPR flex.

Tagovailoa is entering his third NFL season in prime position for a leap forward. Miami was busy improving his supporting cast during the offseason, adding a group that includes superstars Tyreek Hill and Terron Armstead. It might be the saving grace for Tagovailoa considering that he has not been a fantasy factor thus far in his career, registering one weekly finish better than 15th as a rookie and one better than 11th in 2021. He's thus far been very conservative (his 7.0 average depth of throw ranked near the basement of the league last season) and hasn't added much with his legs, but perhaps both will change with Mike McDaniel running the offense. Tagovailoa's youth and improved situation makes him well worth a late flier.

Mostert signed with the Dolphins and the 30-year-old will compete to open the season as the team's lead rusher. Believe it or not, Mostert's career 5.7 YPC is tops in NFL history among all backs with 200-plus carries. Of course, he only has 284 career attempts due primarily to horrific injury luck. Mostert has played more than 11 games in a season once in his career (2019) and missed all but four snaps last season due to an injury. He could handle upward of half the carries and the occasional target (he's never cleared 22 in a single season), with Chase Edmonds and perhaps Myles Gaskin also involved in the offense. Mostert is likely to max out as a flex option and is a poor bet to hold up for the entire season.

The Colts D/ST has finished top 10 in fantasy points each of the last two seasons and hasn't finished worse than 13th since 2017. The success has been powered by forced turnovers, as Indy was top 10 in INTs and turnovers all four years. The Colts struggled to generate pressure and sacks last season, but adding Yannick Ngakoue to the edge room along with 2021 first-round pick Kwity Paye is a step in the right direction. The Colts also have a star up front (DeForest Buckner) and at linebacker (Darius Leonard), as well as a good secondary led by corners Kenny Moore and Stephon Gilmore. The Colts are positioned for a third straight top-10 fantasy campaign.

Moore was selected by the Chiefs in the second round of April's draft. Moore soaked up a massive 32% of the targets during 30 games (three seasons) at Western Michigan. He was utilized both inside and out (39% career slot rate) and showed strong efficiency (his career 90% adjusted catch rate and 2.9 YPRR are both second best in this year's rookie class) and elite hands (four drops on 256 career targets). Moore is on the small side, but he has the biggest hands in this class and showed well athletically at the combine. Moore has a shot at a sizable rookie-season role if he can overtake the likes of JuJu Smith-Schuster, Mecole Hardman and/or Marquez Valdes-Scantling for work. One of Patrick Mahomes' top targets if he progresses well, Moore needs to be on your mid-round radar.

Gage signed with the Buccaneers after spending his first four seasons with Atlanta. The 2018 sixth-round pick had emerged as one of Matt Ryan's go-to targets over the last two seasons, though most of the slot man's work has come in the short range (career 8.5 aDOT) and very little has been near the goal line (nine TDs, 19 end zone targets in his career). Tampa Bay's high-volume, pass-heavy offense has supported three fantasy-relevant wide receivers at times over the last two seasons, though Gage has plenty of competition for work via Mike Evans, Chris Godwin and Julio Jones. Godwin could miss some early action as he recovers from a torn ACL, which could mean early-season WR3 production for Gage, but his ceiling appears limited when all four receivers are healthy.

McManus hasn't delivered a fantasy finish better than ninth in seven full seasons, but he's an obvious candidate for a leap this season with Russell Wilson now leading the Denver offense. McManus has been one of the best kickers in the league over the last three seasons, having nailed 83-of-99 field goals (83.8%) despite a league-high average distance of 41.7. He benefits from the thin Denver air when playing at home, but note that he's actually been better on the road during the span (85.7% with a 41.5 average distance). The 31-year-old is positioned for solid fantasy production in 2022.

The Patriots drafted a kicker in the fifth round of the 2020 draft, but that didn't stop Folk from stealing the gig and emerging as one of the league's top kickers over the last two seasons. Folk, who is now 37 years old, has nailed 62-of-67 field goals during the span. That 92.5% conversion rate is third best in the league during the span, though he has struggled with extra points (90.0%). Last season, New England attempted 39 field goals (third most), which along with his terrific FG accuracy, allowed Folk a second-place fantasy finish -- his first top 10 in over a decade. Folk is a good bet for a step back this season, but he's still a fine starting option in fantasy.

Burks was selected by Tennessee with the 18th overall pick of April's draft. The Arkansas product is big and fast with strong hands and can align all over the field. He handled a hefty 32% target share and led this year's rookie class in yards per route run in 2021. He aligned in the slot 77% of the time during his three seasons, primarily working as a deep threat in his first year before shining as a short-range, RAC weapon the last two seasons. Burks ran a solid 4.55 40-yard dash at 225 pounds (heaviest in the class) at the combine. With A.J. Brown gone, Robert Woods is the Titans' clear No. 1 WR, but Burks very well could pick up a huge target share as a rookie if he develops well. The Titans' run-heavy offense will limit his ceiling a bit, but Burks is a fine bench target.

Lawrence enters 2022 looking for a big second-year leap after a rookie campaign that was overshadowed by the Urban Meyer fiasco. Lawrence was plenty busy in his first season, as the 2021 first-overall pick ranked seventh in pass attempts and fifth in carries among QBs. However, he ranked first in INTs and dealt with a league-high 39 drops, ending up with just 12 passing TDs and some extremely ugly efficiency numbers (33.5 QBR, 6.0 YPA, 60% completion rate). Of course, the struggles are not uncommon for a rookie, and his play improved in the final month of the season. Lawrence's supporting cast will be much better in 2022 with new coach Doug Pederson, as well as Christian Kirk, Travis Etienne Jr., Evan Engram and Brandon Scherff. Lawrence is a breakout candidate worth a look in the later rounds.

Dallas handed Gallup a five-year extension and $23 million guaranteed during the offseason, only months after the perimeter receiver tore his ACL. The commitment to Gallup and the trade of Amari Cooper locks the former into a big role once healthy, but it's fair to expect missed time and/or a slow start considering the injury happened in Week 17. Once back on the field, Gallup will be positioned for a generous target share behind CeeDee Lamb in a productive, high-volume offense. At the same time, Gallup has yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy campaign in four tries and his only top-35 season was back in 2019. Gallup's recovery will need to be evaluated throughout the summer, but we can consider him a good flex/bench option in drafts.

Bass is entering his third NFL season after posting a fourth-place fantasy finish as a rookie and an 11th-place finish in 2021. Bass' accuracy has been ordinary, but he's benefited from tremendous opportunity in Buffalo's high-powered offense. He's finished second in extra-point attempts each of the last two seasons and is seventh in FG attempts during the span. Bass' 84.8% FG conversion rate is just under league average, though he's been terrific on extra points (98.2%). The 2020 sixth-round pick is a solid, young kicker in one of the league's best offenses. He's a starting option in fantasy.

Chark signed with Detroit after an up-and-down first four seasons in Jacksonville. The 2018 second-round pick broke out with a 73-1,008-8 receiving line and 17th-place fantasy finish in 2019, but its been downhill from there. He saw more low-percentage/deep balls in 2020 and, combined with weak QB play (27% off target rate was third highest at WR) and three missed games, he fell outside the top 40 receivers. His 2021 season ended with a broken ankle in Week 4. Chark is a big, fast perimeter target, but his ceiling will be limited with Amon-Ra St. Brown, D'Andre Swift, T.J. Hockenson and inevitably rookie Jameson Williams ahead of him for targets. Chark belongs on benches, though Williams' ACL recovery could allow the 25-year-old some early-season flex value.

Pickens was selected by Pittsburgh in the second round of April's draft. Pickens is a 6-foot-3, vertical receiver who almost exclusively plays outside (his 13% career slot rate is third lowest in this rookie class). We barely saw him in 2021, as he tore his ACL in the spring and appeared in only four games. Most of his damage has come down field (career 14.2 aDOT) and he's shown good hands (two drops on 142 career targets) and ball skills. Pickens has some discipline issues, but he's only 21 years old and can develop as the No. 3 behind Diontae Johnson and Chase Claypool. With the Steelers' quarterback situation a work in progress, Pickens is a longshot for consistent early-career fantasy production, but he has major long-term upside. Consider him with a late-round pick.

The Steelers' D/ST finished 21st in fantasy points last season, which is the unit's worst finish in well over a decade. The fall was a bit of a shock after Pittsburgh finished second in both 2019 and 2020 and it came despite the defense leading the NFL in sacks for the fifth consecutive season. The big dip was related to a major drop in terms of yardage allowed (24th), points allowed (21st) and INTs (15th), which were all categories the Steelers finished top five in the prior two seasons. Most of the team's core (led by stars T.J. Watt, Cameron Heyward and Minkah Fitzpatrick) and Myles Jack and Levi Wallace were added. This is a fringe top-10 fantasy unit.

Landry signed with the Saints. The veteran slot man peaked with five consecutive top-20 fantasy campaigns during 2015-19, but his usage and durability have dipped the past two seasons and he's finished worse than 30th each of the past two seasons. Landry has always been limited a bit by a short-range, slot role (career 7.7 aDOT) and minimal goal-line work (5.3 TDs and 5.4 end zone targets per season), but he's overcome that with massive target shares. He's still been at or above a 24% share in seven straight seasons, which is impressive, but the missed time and career-low TD output (five TDs the last two seasons) have led to the recent slump. Landry is now 29 years old and has more competition than usual for targets with Michael Thomas and Chris Olave in the mix. Landry figures to max out as a PPR flex in deeper leagues.

Fields enters his second NFL season as the clear starter in Chicago. The 2021 first-round pick was about as bad as you can get from a fantasy perspective out of the gate in his career, finishing with single digits in six of his first seven appearances. The light seemed to go on after that, as he finished as a top-12 fantasy QB in each of his final four full games. Despite appearing in only 12 games, Fields ranked fifth among QBs in rushing yards for the season. He obviously as a lot of fantasy appeal due to his rushing, but he was also aggressive as a passer, leading the league with a 9.8 average depth of throw. The dual-threat QB's supporting cast is very weak, but his legs make him a breakout candidate worth considering in the late rounds.

The Chargers' D/ST finished 24th in fantasy points last season, its third straight finish worse than 20th. It was a disappointing effort in defensive-minded coach Brandon Staley's first season, but there were some signs of life, including a third-place finish in forced fumbles and the 11th-best pass rush win rate. The Chargers' 11 INTs placed them 22nd, but the offseason additions of J.C. Jackson (one of three players over the last 20 years with eight-plus INTs in consecutive seasons) and Bryce Callahan helps in a big way. Los Angeles also traded for star Khalil Mack to work opposite Joey Bosa on the edge and upgraded its interior line, which along with star safety Derwin James, sets this unit up for a potential breakout in 2022.

Dotson was selected by Washington with the 16th-overall pick of April's draft. The Penn State product is a small but athletic, versatile and reliable receiver with decent wheels (4.43 40-yard dash). He soaked up a hefty 31% target share in 2021 (after a 30% share in 2020), posting a 91-1182-12 receiving line while hauling in 91% of his catchable targets (second in this rookie class) and dropping only two balls. Terry McLaurin is Washington's top wide receiver and Curtis Samuel is back from injury, so while Dotson has a path to a starting role, he certainly has some competition for targets. Perhaps he'll leap into the WR3/flex mix as a rookie, but he's best viewed as a mid-round bench option.

Higbee enters his sixth NFL season fresh off another ho-hum campaignin which he finished 13th among tight ends in fantasy points -- his third-consecutive finish in the 10-to-20 range. Higbee missed two games (he's missed at least one each of the last three seasons), but still finished no lower than ninth in snaps, routes or receptions. He made his hay near the goal line with a career-high nine end zone targets (fourth most) and five TDs (ninth). Higbee was used more near the line of scrimmage (career-low 5.2 aDOT), which limited his yardage output. The 29-year-old is a better real-life player than fantasy asset and best viewed as a back-end TE2.

Fant was traded to Seattle after spending his first three NFL seasons in Denver. The 2019 first-round pick has been a busy man the last two years, finishing top 10 among tight ends in targets, receptions and yards. Fant's efficiency has been above average despite Denver's QB woes, though his Achilles' heel has been goal-line work and, in turn, touchdowns. Fant has 16 career end zone targets and has yet to clear four TDs in a single season. He is young (24), extremely talented and will be a top-three target in Seattle, but producing a third straight top-12 fantasy campaign may be tough with the Seahawks expected to start QB Drew Lock. Fant is best viewed as a good TE2 with limited short-term upside.

Mattison is entering his fourth NFL season, all of which have been spent as Dalvin Cook's backup in Minnesota. Mattison has been limited to eight career TDs and has yet to manage a top-35 fantasy campaign in the role. He's played at a high level (career 4.2 YPC and 6.6 YPT), but simply hasn't had standalone value when Cook has played. Cook was sidelined for four games in 2021 and Mattison produced 518 yards and three TDs on 105 touches in his stead. He paced all backs in fantasy points during the span. Mattison is extremely young for a fourth-year vet (24), but he'll remain no more than an elite insurance option as long as Cook is in the picture.

The Browns assigned the franchise tag to Njoku this offseason while also releasing ex-starting TE Austin Hooper. The two moves -- along with the acquisition of QB Deshaun Watson (once back from suspension) -- have Njoku in the best position for fantasy success since he finished ninth in 2018. Injuries (15 missed) and Hooper's presence derailed Njoku's production during the 2019-20 seasons, but he bounced back a bit in 2021 thanks to great efficiency -- top five in RAC (6.8) and YPT (9.0) -- and a boost in goal line work (his seven end zone targets ranked 11th). The 2017 first-round pick is still only 26 years old and will be a featured target this season. He's safest as a back-end TE2, but a big leap is possible.

Henderson is entering his fourth season with the Rams. The 2019 third-round pick has seen his role progressively increase throughout his career, but his heavy 2021 usage was related directly to Cam Akers' preseason torn Achilles. During the first half of the season, Henderson was playing three-quarters of the snaps and providing RB2 fantasy production. Injuries cost him all but a few snaps in the second half of the season and he ended up working behind a healed Akers in the Super Bowl. By all accounts, Akers will be the main man in the Los Angeles backfield moving forward, leaving Henderson to situational work. The 25-year-old has some insurance appeal, but likely won't be a weekly flex option.

Prater continues to get the job done, having exited last season with his fourth top-10 fantasy campaign over the last six seasons. Prater's 2021 success was fueled by volume, as Arizona tied for fifth in the league with 37 field goal attempts and sixth with 49 extra-point attempts. Prater has generally been around average in short-to-intermediate kicks in his career, but he's elite from long distance. Over the last decade, he ranks first in attempts (73), conversions (54) and hit rate (74.0%) from 50-plus yards. The 38-year-old returns to Arizona's high-scoring offense in 2022 and is positioned for another good fantasy campaign.

Jones is one of the league's oldest starting wide receivers (32), but you wouldn't know it based on the fact that he's one of only a handful to appear in all 33 regular-season games over the last two years. Jones handled a solid 21% target share during both campaigns and, despite the Jaguars' offensive struggles, has reeled off three consecutive top-35 fantasy seasons. His TDs took a dive last season (four, his lowest since 2016), but it was extremely unlucky (he tied for second in the NFL with 15 end zone targets). Jones' age is a concern, as is added target competition led by Christian Kirk, but an every-down role coupled with a Trevor Lawrence second-year leap would keep Jones in the fantasy discussion. He's a fine bench option.

Miami's D/ST is one of three units to finish top eight in fantasy points each of the last two seasons. That includes a fourth in 2021. The Dolphins predictably saw a dip in INTs last season after pacing the NFL with 18 in 2020, but made up for it with more sacks and six TDs. Fifteen Miami defenders played 400-plus snaps last season and all 15 remain on the 2022 roster. That includes elite CB duo Xavien Howard and Byron Jones, as well as key contributors Christian Wilkins, Jerome Baker, Emmanuel Ogbah and emerging star Jevon Holland. Miami has been dependent on big plays and has a new coaching staff this season, but this is nonetheless a solid unit with upside. Consider it a fringe fantasy starting option.

Jones signed with the Buccaneers after an underwhelming 2021 season in Tennessee. Jones was limited by injuries to 10 games and produced a 31-434-1 receiving line when active. He's now missed 14 games over the last two seasons and has a grand total of four TDs during the span. Jones did flash a bit last season, including a 5-58-1 receiving line on 10 targets in Week 18, but he's now 33 years old and ticketed for a situational role in a Tampa Bay offense that also includes Mike Evans, Chris Godwin and Russell Gage. The high-scoring, pass-heavy Buccaneers' offense is appealing, but Jones figures to be a boom/bust producer. He's only worth a look late in drafts.

The Rams may have won the Super Bowl last season, but their D/ST fell to 17th in fantasy points after four consecutive top-10 campaigns. Los Angeles dipped to mid-pack in yards and points allowed after allowing the fewest in both in 2020. On the plus side, the Rams finished third in both INTs and sacks. The unit still includes star power in the form of elite playmakers Jalen Ramsey, Aaron Donald and newcomer Bobby Wagner, though some juice was lost when Von Miller and Darious Williams signed elsewhere. This is a top-heavy unit, but it has enough firepower to flirt with consistent fantasy success and is worth consideration with one of your final picks.

Smith returns as the top tight end in Minnesota after missing all of 2021 with a knee injury. Smith has thus far been limited to 91 targets in 29 regular-season games (3.1 per game) and has yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy campaign. With Kyle Rudolph sidelined during the final four weeks of 2020, Smith posted a strong 15-183-3 receiving line and was TE4 in fantasy, though he was out-targeted 22-to-20 by Tyler Conklin. Of course, Rudolph and Conklin are gone, which positions Smith for a big boost in usage in 2022. The 2019 second-round pick is still very young (entering his age-23 season) and makes for a solid TE2 with room for more.

Robinson was selected by Washington in the third round of April's draft. Robinson is a huge power back, who ranked at or near the top of this year's rookie class in weight (225 pounds), hand size and wingspan. He was used sparingly during his first three seasons at Alabama, but emerged as lead back in 2021, posting a 271-1,343-14 rushing line in 14 games, adding 35-296-2 as a receiver. Robinson has sufficient speed for his size and his collegiate elusiveness and tackle breaking numbers were both strong. Robinson seemed to pass Antonio Gibson on the depth chart during Training Camp, but a gunshot wound will cost him at least four weeks of the regular season. Stash Robinson on your bench or IR, if possible, as it's possible he'll be an RB2/flex option later this season.

McKissic re-signed with Washington and will return as the team's primary passing-down back. The 28-year-old has been busy in the role over the last two seasons, ranking no lower than second among backs in targets, receptions and receiving yards in 2020 and no lower than sixth in the three categories prior to a suffering a season-ending injury last season. McKissic is severely limited as a rusher (he's never cleared 85 carries in a season and has four career rushing TDs) and his ceiling is limited by the presence of early-down and goal-line backs Brian Robinson Jr. (once healthy) and Antonio Gibson. Of course, even with Gibson around, McKissic was 17th in fantasy points in 2020 and 22nd prior to the injury last season. McKissic's role will allow him to occasionally flirt with PPR flex value.

Palmer is entering his second NFL season after spending most of his rookie campaign as the Chargers' No. 4 wide receiver. The 2021 third-round pick will again be competing with the same three receivers he worked behind last season, and while he won't pass Keenan Allen and Mike Williams on the depth chart, Jalen Guyton's No. 3 role is attainable. That's especially the case after Palmer flashed on the rare occasions he played a big role. He was on the field for more than 60% of pass plays in three games and posted 5-66-1, 5-43-1 and 4-45-1 receiving lines during those outings. Palmer is only 22 years old and, while standalone value will be tough early on, he's one injury away from a major role in the Chargers' high-scoring, Justin Herbert-led offense. Consider drafting him late.

Winston re-signed with the Saints and will return as the team's starting QB. His fantasy production was extremely inconsistent last season, as he posted a pair of top-five outings, but was 16th or worse during his other four full games prior to tearing his ACL in Week 8. Winston did play pretty well prior to the injury (fifth-best QBR) and he'll have a better group of targets with Michael Thomas, Jarvis Landry and rookie Chris Olave now in the fold. Winston's last full season (2019) resulted in a fifth-place fantasy finish and while he's unlikely to match that same volume, his aggressive nature (top six in average depth of throw in all six seasons) offers some hope for fantasy-relevance. He's best viewed as a late-round flier.

Parker was traded to New England after spending his first seven seasons in Miami. He hasn't quite lived up to expectations since being selected in the first round back in 2015, having managed to finish just one season better than 40th in fantasy points (11th in 2019). Durability has been the main issue, as he appeared in 100% of Miami's regular-season games in only one of his seven campaigns there. That includes seven missed games in 2021. Parker was a top-35 fantasy WR during 10 active weeks last season and could emerge as Mac Jones' top perimeter/vertical target, but his age (29) and durability woes are obvious concerns. He's fine for your bench, but expect inconsistent production.

Williams signed with Detroit prior to last season and immediately stepped in as a situational back behind D'Andre Swift. The two were active together for 10 games and though they were about even in carries those weeks, Swift played 197 more snaps (413 to 216) and saw 42 more targets (64 to 22). Whereas Swift was fourth among RBs in fantasy points those weeks, Williams was 30th. Williams has generally averaged 10-to-11 touches per game throughout his career and that's what we should expect in 2022. Barring a major Swift injury, the 27-year-old is a long shot for his first career top-30 fantasy campaign.

There's really no other way to say it: Anderson had arguably the most inefficient season by any wide receiver in the league in 2021. Anderson ranked sixth in both snaps and routes, but was 28th in targets, 44th in receptions and 64th in yards. His 48% catch rate, 4.7 yards per target and 0.9 yards per route run were all 87th or worse among 91 qualified wide receivers. Anderson has 18th- and 19th-place fantasy seasons on his resume, but has been 39th or worse three of the past four seasons. It's hard to get too excited here, but perhaps the arrival of Baker Mayfield will help Anderson to a bounceback. His top-20 fantasy showing in Matt Rhule's offense in 2020 also adds some hope, but he's too risky to consider before the later rounds.

Ryan was traded to the Colts after spending his first 14 seasons with the Falcons. He has delivered the occasional big fantasy season during his career (second place in 2016 and 2018), but he's also finished 11th or worse five of the last seven seasons despite often ranking near the top of the league in pass attempts. That's especially a concern as he heads to a run-heavy Indianapolis offense that will continue to lean heavily on Jonathan Taylor. Ryan is now 37 years old and has never cleared 147 rushing yards in a single season. He's an upgrade for the Colts, but is not in a good spot from a fantasy perspective. Consider him a fringe QB2 with limited upside.

The Eagles selected Gainwell in the fifth round of the 2021 draft and utilized him in spurts throughout his rookie campaign. Gainwell played more than 40% of the snaps in only three games and was limited to five weekly fantasy finishes better than 38th. He totaled 544 yards on 101 touches and was a bit lucky in the TD department (six TDs, 3.5 expected). Gainwell will battle for a larger share of the pie this season, but Miles Sanders and Boston Scott will both be involved as well. The Eagles' run-heavy scheme makes Gainwell a fine bench hold, though his 191-pound frame is likely to limit him to situational duties throughout his career.

Mayfield was traded to Carolina and will take over as the team's starting QB after spending his first four NFL seasons in Cleveland. The 2018 first-overall pick has flashed at times (especially late in the 2020 season), but inconsistent play and a lack of rushing contributions (571 yards and 5 TDs in 60 games) has left him without a single top-15 fantasy campaign. Mayfield is aggressive (career 8.8 average depth of throw) and a potential breakout 2021 season was derailed by injury, so a sliver of hope remains for the 27-year-old. Mayfield's offensive line won't be as good in Carolina, but he does have a good group of targets led by DJ Moore, Christian McCaffrey and Robbie Anderson. Mayfield is only worth drafting late in superflex leagues.

Jones was the fifth QB selected in the 2021 draft, but no rookie passer was more impressive last season. The Alabama product was, at worst, average in notable categories like QBR (51.0), YPA (7.3) and completion rate (68%), the latter of which was eighth best in the league. The bad news is that Jones unsurprisingly was a nonfactor with his legs (15 scrambles in 17 games). His fantasy production was extremely boom/bust and included five top-10 weeks, as well as 10 finishes of 22nd or worse. Jones will need elite passing numbers in order to reach QB1 status, and while that's possible (adding DeVante Parker helps), it's obviously unlikely. He's worth no more than a late-round flier.

Believe it or not, Tannehill has finished as a top-12 fantasy QB each of the past two seasons. However, we saw a pretty large step back in his production in 2021. Tannehill fell from 33 passing TDs in 2020 to 21 last season, while his INTs doubled (seven to 14) and his sack total nearly did as well (24 to 47). He finished 15th in fantasy PPG after top-10 showings the prior two seasons. Tannehill suffers a bit from Tennessee's extremely run-heavy offense, though he's made up some ground with seven rushing TDs each of the last two seasons. Especially with A.J. Brown gone, Tannehill is best viewed as a QB2 and won't be anything more than an occasional streaming option in most formats.

Wentz was traded to Washington after spending one season with the Colts. His 2021 showing was a big step forward after a rough 2020 with Philadelphia, but he still wasn't much of a fantasy factor, finishing 13th despite appearing in all 17 games. Volume was a problem in Indianapolis' run-heavy offense and, while that may change in Washington, it may not be enough to overcome mediocre efficiency and rushing contributions. Wentz will benefit from a good offensive line and solid supporting cast led by Terry McLaurin, but he's a long shot to deliver what would be his third career top-12 fantasy campaign. He's a fringe QB2.

After posting 70-1,063-5 (2018) and 65-1,190-11 (2019) receiving lines during his first two full NFL seasons, Golladay had the look of a long-term superstar. Instead, he was limited to five games in 2020 due to injury before missing three more games and struggling badly to produce in the Giants' horrific offense in 2021. Golladay went from ranking first at the position in touchdowns and third in end zone targets (15) in 2019 to failing to score a single TD in 2021. Golladay is now 28 years old and has struggled with durability for two seasons, but it's hard to throw in the towel on a 6-foot-4 vertical target who has had his level of success. There's at least hope for a rebound with Brian Daboll in town, so Golladay is a worthwhile late-round dart throw.

An underrated aspect of Bill Belichick's legacy is his ability to get the most out of what often seems like an average defense on paper. New England's D/ST has finished as a top-12 fantasy unit nine times over the last 10 seasons. That includes a third-place finish in 2021 that was powered by 10 top-10 weeks (second most). New England has at least 18 INTs in four consecutive seasons (only four other teams have done this over the last 20 years) and has finished no worse than 10th in points allowed since 2012. New England's defense again looks "just OK" on paper (star CB J.C. Jackson is obviously a huge loss), but history shows Belichick is a good bet to keep this unit near the top. Consider it a fringe starting option.

Hardman is entering his fourth NFL season having yet to live up to the expectations that come with being the second-round pick in one of the league's best pass offenses. The lack of emergence doesn't necessarily seem to be his fault, however, as he's yet to miss a single game (an impressive feat) and trails only Deebo Samuel in RAC (8.6) over the last three seasons. Hardman's three seasons of low target shares (he hasn't cleared 13% in a season) are a red flag, but the departure of Tyreek Hill certainly opens up a major opportunity in what is Hardman's first contract year. The 25-year-old is what he's been the last three draft seasons: a fine late-round flier.

Herbert was on the field for 300 offensive snaps after Chicago selected him in the sixth round of the 2021 draft. The 24-year-old spent most of the season picking up the scraps behind feature back David Montgomery, though he saw extended action during the four weeks Montgomery was out with an injury. Herbert reached 18 carries and 70 rushing yards in all four games, but a lack of scoring (one TD) and receiving work (10 targets) limited him to the 18th-most fantasy points among RBs during the span. Herbert appears to be a solid backfield option, so there's some insurance appeal here, but he won't have standalone value as long as Montgomery is healthy.

Doubs was selected by Green Bay in the fourth round of April's draft. Doubs is a vertical, perimeter receiver with good size, speed and hands. He aligned on the perimeter 85% of the time at Nevada and ran a deep route 43% of the time (second highest in this rookie class). He was never short for volume, having seen 75-plus targets in each of his four seasons. Doubs finished his career with 58-1002-9 and 80-1109-11 receiving lines, having cleared 24% of the team targets and 39% of the air yards both seasons. Doubs was also a standout punt returner. The Packers' WR situation is wide open, so if Doubs develops quickly, he could play significant snaps as a rookie. Keep him stashed in dynasty and monitor his progress this summer.

Allgeier was selected by Atlanta in the fifth round of April's draft. The BYU product was one of the most effective and efficient backs in this class during his collegiate career, concluding with a strong 2021 season. He ranked no lower than second in carries (276), rushing yards (1,606) and rushing TDs (23), while showing well in YAC (3.5), broken tackles and elusiveness last season. Allgeier isn't the fastest (4.60 40-yard dash) and he's a work in progress as a receiver, but he's 224 pounds and has a path to a big rookie-season role on a depth chart led by over-age-30 backs Cordarrelle Patterson and Damien Williams. Allgeier is a sleeper to lead Atlanta in carries in 2022 and is well worth a late pick in season-long formats.

Hurst has signed with the Bengals after two seasons each with the Ravens and Falcons. The 2018 first-round pick has yet to emerge into a consistent fantasy asset, but bad timing has been the main culprit. Hurst was drafted by Baltimore the same year as Mark Andrews, who obviously stole the show. He was then traded to Atlanta and broke out with a 56-571-6 receiving line and 10th-place fantasy finish in 2020. Of course, the Falcons then drafted Kyle Pitts and Hurst was out of a starting job. The 29-year-old is now positioned as the starter in a good Cincinnati offense, which sets the sure-handed (one career drop) tight end as an intriguing post-hype sleeper. Consider him late in deeper drafts.

The Washington D/ST was a major disappointment last season, falling from fourth in fantasy points in 2020 to 22nd in 2021. Injuries were a culprit, as star edge rushers Chase Young and Montez Sweat both missed nearly half the season. In turn, Washington was average or worse in nearly every category, which included a fall from sixth to 17th in sacks and fifth to 22nd in INTs. The good news is that Washington's defense looks pretty good on paper, especially with 14 of the top 16 in 2021 snaps still on the roster. Once healthy, Young will join Sweat, Jonathan Allen and Daron Payne to form one of the league's best defensive lines, and Kendall Fuller, William Jackson and Kamren Curl lead a solid secondary. This is a fringe top-10 fantasy unit.

Denver hasn't had a dominant D/ST since 2016, but the unit overcame key injuries and the departure of Von Miller en route to a solid 14th-place finish in 2021. That included eight top-10 outings (tied for fifth). Despite playing in a tough AFC West, Denver allowed the eighth-fewest yards and third-fewest points last season, but struggled to create turnovers (21st) and sacks (18th). Offseason addition Randy Gregory should help with the latter and helps fill out a solid overall defense that is a little light on star power (Justin Simmons the obvious exception), but solid or better on all levels. This is a midrange fantasy unit with top-10 potential if second-year players Patrick Surtain II and Baron Browning make a leap.

Jones finally appeared to be on the verge of a breakout last season, opening 2021 with at least 21 fantasy points in three of his first four games. The wheels fell off from there, as he failed to produce another top-12 outing before missing the final six games due to injury. Durability is a real concern, as he's missed at least two games during each of his three NFL seasons. Jones has yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy campaign, but there is a sliver of hope here after New York hired Brian Daboll as head coach. Also, much like Daboll's previous QB, Josh Allen, Jones' legs are an asset; he ranks sixth at the position with 1,000 rushing yards since 2019. Jones is worth a look only as a QB2 toward the end of your draft.

The Bengals' D/ST finished 19th in fantasy points in 2021 and has now gone six consecutive seasons without a top 10. Despite the lack of recent production, there's reason for optimism that this unit will be fantasy-relevant in 2022. For starters, after years of horrendous production, the unit made a leap in nearly every category last season, including top-15 finishes in INTs and sacks. More importantly, the defense looks good on paper, with 14 of the top 15 players in snaps on the AFC Championship roster set to return. The defense is led by terrific duos at edge (Sam Hubbard, Trey Hendrickson), safety (Jessie Bates and Vonn Bell) and tackle (D.J. Reader, B.J. Hall) and are solid at corner and linebacker. The Bengals' D/ST is a fringe starting option.

Cleveland made major defensive additions last offseason and the result was the best fantasy campaign by its D/ST in over a decade (13th). The unit was near mid-pack in most categories, but shined in sacks (ninth most), pass rush win rate (third best) and yards allowed (fifth fewest). Cleveland wasn't as aggressive this past offseason, but it didn't need to be, with 10 of the top 12 in 2021 snaps back on the roster. The unit has stars (Myles Garrett, Denzel Ward, John Johnson III), as well as several emerging recent early-round picks (Jeremiah Owusu-Koramoah, Greg Newsome II, Grant Delpit). Cleveland's D/ST has the look of a good streaming option.

Engram signed a one-year deal with the Jaguars after five seasons with the Giants. He appeared destined for stardom when he produced a rookie tight end-record 174 fantasy points back in 2017. Instead, he's struggled with injuries and the Giants' weak offense en route to four straight fantasy finishes of 13th or worse. The 2017 first-round pick has settled in as a short/intermediate target and hasn't been used near the goal line (no more than three TDs or three end zone targets in a season since 2017). Engram will benefit from new coach Doug Pederson's very TE-friendly offense (career 31% TE target share in eight seasons), though the 28-year-old is no more than a late-round lottery ticket.

Since the start of the 2017 season, Gano has converted 103-of-111 FG attempts. That 92.8% hit rate trails only Justin Tucker for best in the NFL and stands even after we adjust for distance. The elite accuracy has been a necessity for Gano, as the New York offense has given him almost no help; the Giants have ranked dead-last in extra-point attempts each of the past two seasons. Gano converted all but two of the 40 extra points and also ranks sixth in made field goals (60) since the start of 2020, which has powered him to the 14th-most fantasy points during the span. New York's offense figures to be better under Brian Daboll, so coupled with terrific accuracy, 35-year-old Gano is a fringe starting option in fantasy.

Pacheco was selected by the Chiefs in the seventh round of April's draft. Pacheco is a big, fast back who posted the best speed score in this class at the combine (4.37 40-yard dash at 216 pounds). He was a factor in the Rutgers backfield during all four seasons at the school, ending up with a 563-2442-18 rushing line and 47-249-1 receiving line. Pacheco's collegiate efficiency was about as poor as it gets (4.3 YPC and 3.7 YPT are both worst in this class), though he had little help (his 1.6 yards before contact is easily lowest in the class). Pacheco was also weak in the YAC and FMT categories, but added some value as a returner and pass blocker. He'll battle for touches behind Clyde Edwards-Helaire and perhaps Ronald Jones.

Okwuegbunam was the big winner of the Russell Wilson/Noah Fant trade, as the third-year tight end will have much-improved QB play while also replacing Fant as Denver's No. 1 tight end. The 2020 fourth-round pick has flashed in 18 career games; his 7.2 RAC ranks first and his 80% catch rate third among 51 tight ends with 50-plus targets over the last two seasons. Okwuegbunam very well could cap out as a TE2, especially with third-round rookie Greg Dulcich eventually in the mix and with Denver so strong at wide receiver, but a full-on third-year breakout is certainly possible. Consider Okwuegbunam with one of your final picks.

Watson was traded to Cleveland after sitting out the entire 2021 season. Prior to the lost year, Watson finished as a top-five fantasy QB in three straight seasons and it could have been four if not for a torn ACL as a rookie in 2017. The dual-threat playmaker ranked no lower than sixth among QBs in rushing yards in each of his last three seasons, while adding 15 TDs with his legs along the way. Watson's passing ability showed continual improvement, as he paced the NFL in passing yards (4,823) and YPA (8.9), while posting 33 TDs and just 7 INTs in 2020. Amari Cooper aside, Watson doesn't have a standout group of targets in Cleveland, but the offensive line is outstanding and his rushing prowess supplies him with elite fantasy upside. Watson will be suspended for the first 11 games of the season, so he's only worth stashing in deep superflex leagues.

Hooper signed with the Titans after spending four seasons in Atlanta and the last two with Cleveland. The 2016 third-round pick's fantasy stock took a dive with the Browns, as he followed up a pair of sixth-place fantasy finishes with Atlanta (2018-19) with a pair of finishes outside the top 20 the last two seasons. There were a variety of reasons for the decline, including a drop in targets, a dip in efficiency and shaky durability (seven missed games over the last three seasons). Hooper's upside will be limited in the Titans' run-heavy scheme, though coach Mike Vrabel's TE units in Tennessee have averaged a hefty 24% target share in his four seasons. Hooper is a low-ceiling, fringe TE2.

Moore appeared in 14 games and was on the field for 37% of Arizona's snaps as a rookie last season. The second-round pick was almost exclusively limited to short-range/gadget plays, as 51% of his 65 targets were screens, 25% of his touches were carries and his 1.3 average depth of target was lowest among 91 qualified wide receivers. Moore's lack of vertical targets and goal-line work (one end zone target) severely limited his fantasy output (three top-40 outings). Moore is only 22 years old and his best days are likely ahead of him, but he may not have a path to a substantially larger role this season with DeAndre Hopkins, Marquise Brown, A.J. Green and Zach Ertz in the fold. He's not worth considering until the last few rounds of your draft.

Tonyan entered last season as the poster boy for regression to the mean, and boy did he take that to heart. One season after posting a 52-586-11 receiving line in 16 games, Tonyan plummeted to 18-204-2 in eight games prior to suffering a torn ACL. Tonyan's huge dip in scoring is obvious, but his catch rate (88% to 62%) and YPT (9.9 to 7.0) also crashed back to earth. His targets were almost identical during the two seasons (3.7 in 2020, 3.6 in 2021) and so, even with Davante Adams gone, it's hard to expect much of an increase this season. The 28-year-old will have some touchdown upside as long as Aaron Rodgers is his quarterback, but he's best viewed as a mid-to-back-end TE2.

It's not often we talk about 32-year-old running backs in fantasy, but Ingram is still hanging around.  The 2011 first-round pick opened last season in Houston, but was traded back to New Orleans and appeared in four games along with Alvin Kamara. Ingram handled 28 carries (27% share) and nine targets (8%) in those weeks and was 47th in fantasy points during the span. He played two full games with Kamara out and was very effective, producing 100-plus yards and a top-15 fantasy performance both weeks. Ingram isn't a candidate for consistent fantasy production at his age, but with Kamara facing a possible suspension, he could find his way to the RB2/flex radar early in the season. For that reason only, he's worth late-round consideration in drafts.

Tolbert was selected by Dallas in the third round of April's draft. The South Alabama product's four collegiate seasons culminated with a 82-1474-8 showing in 2021. The yardage total was highest in this year's rookie class. Massively utilized, Tolbert handled a target share of at least 33% and an air-yard share of at least 53% in both 2020 and 2021. He's 6-foot-1 with 10-inch hands, decent wheels and the ability to play inside or out, but is a bit older than most rookies, faced light competition and will need to clean up the drops (eight in 2021). Tolbert's chief competition for No. 3 duties in a good Dallas offense is James Washington (who will miss some time), so there's potential Year 1 fantasy value here (especially if Michael Gallup's ACL recovery costs him game time). Keep him on your radar in the late rounds.

Goff is back as the starting QB in Detroit. The ex-Ram appeared in 14 games last season and was limited to one weekly fantasy finish better than eighth (Week 1) and two others better than 12th. Goff was extremely conservative, as his 6.5 average depth of throw was lowest in the NFL. It's possible that increases with improved targets this season, but that's far from a lock considering he was at 6.4 in his final season with the Rams. Goff is also a non-factor as a rusher, having yet to clear 108 rushing yards in a single season. He's barely on the QB2 radar.

After spending four years as Pitt's starting quarterback, Pickett was selected by the Steelers with the 20th pick of April's draft. Pickett enjoyed a breakout 2021 campaign, totaling 47 TDs and 4,319 pass yards. His 81.2 QBR was best in this rookie class and his 1.4% INT rate was second best. He's primarily a pocket passer, but he's a good athlete and was one of four QBs in this class to scramble for over 400 yards last season. Small hands (8.5") and age (easily oldest among the top QB prospects) are knocks, but that's more than offset by his strong passing efficiency. Pickett will compete with Mitchell Trubisky to replace Ben Roethlisberger as the Steelers' starting QB and the history of first-round QBs suggests he'll be under center full time by mid-season. He's only worth drafting in superflex and dynasty leagues.

Collins is entering his second NFL season after appearing in 14 games as a rookie. The 2021 third-round pick played a situational role in his first season, clearing five targets in only three games. A 6-foot-4, 222-pound perimeter receiver, Collins was sent deep often (12th-highest average depth of route), but simply wasn't thrown at much, and even when he was, 26% were off target (fifth highest). Collins enters 2022 with a clear path to an every-down role opposite Brandin Cooks. Of course, his prospects will revolve around how well Davis Mills plays in his second season. Collins is a bit of a lottery ticket well worth late-round consideration.

Beckham remains a free agent. He continues to show up with spurts of greatness, but injuries have derailed his career. Beckham has played two full seasons in his career and has appeared in 53 of 81 possible games (65%) over the last five seasons. Beckham's latest injury was a torn ACL suffered in the Super Bowl, an injury that makes him a long shot to be ready for the first weeks (if not months) of the 2022 season. Beckham was fantasy's No. 22 WR during seven full games with the Rams last season, so there's hope for fantasy-relevance once he's back, but that's not enough to consider the 29-year-old prior to the final few rounds of your draft.

Everett signed with the Chargers after four seasons with the Rams and a one-year stop in Seattle. Incredibly, Everett's reception and yardage totals have increased every season he's been in the league. He also posted career-high marks in targets, touchdowns and catch rate (75%) last season. Everett has generally been utilized as a short-range target (career 6.7 aDOT) and not much near the goal line (18 career end zone targets), which has left him without a top-20 fantasy campaign. Of course, he's now positioned as the top receiving tight end in an elite Chargers' offense. The 28-year-old is in the TE2 mix and has some late-round appeal.

Wilson is entering his second NFL season after a rocky rookie campaign in which he struggled with efficiency and missed four games with an injury. The 2021 second-overall pick was limited to nine passing TDs and 11 INTs and ranked among the worst QBs in completion rate (56%), YPA (6.1), sack rate (10.3%) and drop rate (6.3%). Poor rookie-season pass efficiency isn't a major concern, so a big second-year leap is very possible. Wilson added some value with legs (including four TDs) as a rookie and his 2022 prospects are heightened by an improved supporting cast led by Elijah Moore and early-round rookies Garrett Wilson and Breece Hall. Same as most high-pedigree, second-year QBs, Wilson is worth late-round consideration.

Likely was selected by the Ravens in the fourth round of April's draft. He is one of the most accomplished pass catchers in this rookie class and that was highlighted by a 59-912-12 receiving line in 2021. He handled a hefty 25% target share, paced this TE class with a 3.4 YPRR and posted a 11.5 YPT (third best). Likely scored at least five TDs in all four seasons at Coastal Carolina while running nearly half of his routes from the slot. He is a bit undersized and may not emerge as an impact blocker, but he's a decent athlete (class-best 36-inch vertical at the combine) with good speed and receiving skills. An impressive offseason has Likely positioned as the Raven's possible No. 3 receiver, so folks in two-TE leagues can draft him.

Burkhead re-signed with Houston after emerging as the team's feature back in the second half of last season. He soaked up 122 carries, which was nearly double his previous career high of 74. Burkhead was serviceable in the role, but had atrocious help (1.43 yards before contact was fourth worst among RBs) and wasn't a big factor as a receiver (32 targets in 16 games). He ended up with one weekly fantasy finish better than 24th. Burkhead is now 32 years old and likely to play a reduced role with impressive rookie Dameon Pierce added to the fold. There's minimal fantasy appeal here.

Mariota is competing with third-round rookie Desmond Ridder to replace Matt Ryan as the Falcons' starting QB. Mariota has barely seen the field since losing the starting gig in Tennessee in 2019. He's played extended snaps in one game over the last two seasons and showed well in that 2020 Week 15 outing (226 passing yards, 88 rushing yards and a pair of TDs). Of course, prior to that, the 2015 second-overall pick struggled during five seasons in Tennessee. Mariota has been effective with his legs throughout his career (264-1,574-13 rushing line), but that has yet to translate to a top-12 fantasy campaign (he's finished better than 18th once). We shouldn't expect that to change in Atlanta's rebuilding offense. He's not a good QB2 option.

White was selected by Tampa Bay in the third round of April's draft. He is a big back with huge hands who lacks experience; he totaled 224 carries and 57 targets during 15 games at Arizona State. Most of that damage was done in 2021, as he posted a 182-1006-15 rushing line while adding 43-456-1 in the passing game. White's rushing efficiency was pedestrian for the most part, though he eluded tackles at a good rate. He has the look of an impact receiving back in the pros, though he'll struggle for playing time for a while. Leonard Fournette is the Buccaneers' feature back, Giovani Bernard will help in obvious passing situations and 2020 third-round pick Ke'Shawn Vaughn is also in the mix. White doesn't have much season-long value, but is a fine dynasty hold.

Watkins signed with the Packers after one unsuccessful season in Baltimore, as he was limited to career-low marks in receptions, receiving yards and touchdowns. Watkins missed four games and has now been sidelined for multiple games in six of his last seven seasons. He hasn't produced a top-40 fantasy campaign since 2015 and he's never finished better than 20th. On paper, the 29-year-old is in a good spot with Aaron Rodgers under center and with the likes of Allen Lazard, Randall Cobb and a pair of rookies as his chief competition for snaps and targets. However, he's been here before many times and hasn't come through. Watkins may flash with the occasional big game, but he's barely worth considering late in your draft.

Drake signed with the Ravens during the offseason. The 28-year-old was expected to play a fairly significant offensive role in Las Vegas 2021, but ended up with 93 touches in 12 games while working behind feature back Josh Jacobs. Even when Jacobs was sidelined during Weeks 2 and 3, Drake shared the backfield with Peyton Barber and was limited to 112 yards on 23 touches. The season was a big letdown for a player who had been a top-20 fantasy back each of the prior three seasons. Drake now becomes a longshot for fantasy relevance, but with Gus Edwards on IR and J.K. Dobbins' health uncertain leading into Week 1, it's possible he and Mike Davis handle a generous share of the touches early in the season. Drake is only worth stashing in deep leagues.

White was selected by Las Vegas in the fourth round of April's draft. White is a tough, power runner who impressed at the combine with a 4.40-yard dash (114 speed score) and class-best 128-inch broad jump. The Georgia product has already torn both ACLs, his advanced rushing stats are mediocre and he's a non-factor as a pass catcher (17 catches in three seasons). On the plus side, he was stopped for a loss on a class-low 9% of his carries in 2021. Even if he develops into an effective pro rusher, White is a likely committee back, and usage/production similar to Jordan Howard may be his ceiling. He's not much more than an insurance RB in the short term, but with Jacobs entering a contract year, White is well worth stashing in dynasty.

The 10th-place finish by the Titans' D/ST in 2021 was its third top 12 over the last four seasons. Tennessee has finished no lower than 10th in INTs each of the last three seasons and was top 12 in sacks, yards allowed, points allowed and touchdowns last season. Tennessee's success was fueled by the likes of Jeffery Simmons, Harold Landry III, Denico Autry, Kevin Byard and Amani Hooker, four of whom are back for 2022 (Landry tore his ACL and is out for the season). The unit will also have a healthy Bud Dupree and Caleb Farley after both missed extended action last season. Tennessee didn't make any major offseason veteran additions, but keeping its core of stars in place sets the Titans up with a solid defense and suggests they'll remain a viable streaming option again in 2022.

After one-year stops in Dallas and Houston, Cobb was traded back to Green Bay (his home for his first eight NFL seasons) prior to 2021. Unsurprisingly, the reunion with Aaron Rodgers didn't lead to much fantasy success. Cobb was limited to 39 targets while primarily working in a situational role. He also missed five games and hasn't played a full season since he was 25 years old back in 2015. Cobb is now entering his age-32 campaign and hasn't been a top-40 fantasy receiver since 2017. He theoretically has a path to more work with Davante Adams gone, but that seems like a long shot considering his age and durability woes, as well as the acquisitions of Sammy Watkins, Christian Watson and Romeo Doubs. Cobb can be avoided in all but the deepest of PPR leagues.

Mack signed with Houston after five seasons in Indianapolis. He has had some success in the pros, posting 195-908-9 and 247-1,091-8 rushing lines during the 2018 and 2019 seasons, respectively. A torn ACL in Week 1 of 2020 followed by the rise of Jonathan Taylor left Mack without a role and he's been held to 37 touches on 68 snaps over the last two seasons. Mack has proven to be an effective rusher (career 4.4 YPC, 1.8 YAC), but he's a nonfactor as a receiver (83 career targets), which along with shaky durability (two-plus missed games in all five NFL seasons) has left him without a top-20 fantasy campaign. With 32-year-old Rex Burkhead and Day 3 rookie Dameon Pierce as his chief competition, Mack has a legitimate path to leading the team in carries. The 26-year-old's ceiling is limited, but he could flirt with flex numbers in non-PPR leagues.

Williams was selected by Detroit with the 12th overall pick of April's draft. After inexplicably being limited to 15 catches during two seasons at Ohio State, Williams exploded for a 79-1572-15 campaign at Alabama in 2021. Williams' rare combination of height, elite speed and quickness make him a major threat for explosive plays. That was on display last season, as he averaged 19.9 yards per reception, a class-best 13.1 yards per target and 9.5 yards after the catch. Williams tore his ACL in the national title game, but the former hurdler is only 21 years old and won't be rushed by a rebuilding Detroit team. Expect a slow start for Williams (he'll miss at least four games while on the NFI list), but he has elite upside and figures to be a fixture in fantasy lineups by midseason.

Green re-signed with Arizona after a relatively successful 2021 campaign with the team. Green played 80% of the snaps during 16 active games and his 54-848-3 receiving line allowed a 41st-place finish in fantasy. He was primarily utilized as an intermediate/deep threat and his 15.7 YPR was 10th highest among wideouts. Green has ranked no lower than 13th at the position in end zone targets each of his last four seasons. He will play a lesser role this season after the acquisition of Marquise Brown, though he'll see a boost in work during DeAndre Hopkins' six-game suspension to open the season. Green's upside is limited at age 34, but he figures to hang on the flex radar while Hopkins is out.

Jones signed with the Chiefs after four unceremonious fantasy seasons in Tampa Bay. The 2018 second-round pick peaked with a pair of top-25 fantasy campaigns in 2019 and 2020, but he took a back seat to Leonard Fournette last season and was limited to 111 touches. Despite falling out of favor in Tampa Bay, there is hope for Jones, as he's shown to be an effective rusher and is still pretty young (25). Also, he's joining an elite offense that doesn't have a proven long-term answer at running back. Clyde Edwards-Helaire is the favorite for lead-back duties, but his inconsistent production and durability woes present Jones an opportunity for substantial work. He's well worth a late-round flier in deeper leagues.

Watson was selected by Green Bay in the second round of April's draft. The North Dakota State product was one of the biggest winners at the combine, measuring in at 6-foot-4 with 10 1/8-inch hands while showing well in every athletic drill. The latter included a 4.36 40-yard dash and class-best 136-inch broad jump. Watson was utilized in a variety of ways during four seasons at NDSU. He was a vertical threat (career 20.5 YPR on 104 catches), ball carrier (49 carries) and kick returner (27 attempts). He played at a "small" school, but his outstanding combination of size, speed, athleticism and versatility makes him an intriguing prospect. He has a path to an every-down role in an elite Packers' offense, as his top competition is oft-injured Allen Lazard, Randall Cobb and Sammy Watkins, but it may take him a while to earn that role after missing a lot of preseason action. Watson should be on your radar in the late rounds.

Pierce was selected by the Colts in the second round of April's draft. He is a big receiver who is more vertical/contested catch than he is quickness/separation. He never had an aDOT below 14.7 during four seasons at Cincinnati and he handled at least 24% of the team's air yards when active each of the last three seasons. That includes a 36% share while delivering a 52-884-8 receiving line in 2021. Pierce crushed it at the combine with a class-best 40.5-inch vertical and 4.41 40-yard dash at 211 pounds. Granted, his ceiling will be limited by the Colts' run-heavy offense, but Pierce has a path to every-down snaps as the team's likely No. 2 wide receiver behind Michael Pittman Jr. With Matt Ryan in town, Pierce very well could flirt with occasional flex value. He's worth a look in the late rounds.

After playing sparingly as a rookie in 2020, Jefferson was on the field for 84% of the Rams' pass plays and handled 89 targets last season. The former second-round pick was primarily utilized as a situational deep threat, posting a 13.3 average depth of target (14th highest among WRs) and averaging 16.0 yards per reception (seventh). Jefferson finished 36th in fantasy points, though that number would've been much worse had Robert Woods not been lost for the season just hours after the Rams traded for Jefferson's replacement (Odell Beckham Jr.). Jefferson has yet to miss a game and has the look of a solid player, but he's behind at least Cooper Kupp and Allen Robinson II for targets, and a major boost in production seems unlikely for the 26-year-old. He's worth a bench spot only.

Hubbard was selected in the fourth round of the 2021 draft and, much like Mike Davis the year prior, he was asked to soak up significant snaps in place of an injured Christian McCaffrey.
