Hubbard was not overly impressive in the role, ranking near the basement of the league in YPC (3.6), YAC (1.3) and YPT (5.0) while pacing all backs in drops (seven). He failed to post a weekly fantasy finish better than 15th and deferred substantial playing time to scat back Ameer Abdullah in the second half of the season. Perhaps Hubbard will make a Year 2 leap, but even if McCaffrey misses more time, the 23-year-old will need to compete with newcomer D'Onta Foreman for work. Hubbard belongs on waivers.

Thomas enters 2022 eyeing a rebound campaign after last season was derailed by multiple injuries. Thomas was seventh in fantasy points through three weeks before a hamstring injury knocked him out until Week 12. He returned for two games before suffering a torn ACL. Thomas is now 31 years old and his early-season availability and effectiveness are in question, but he's a good bet to return to the TE1 mix when healthy. In his breakout 2021, Thomas led all tight ends in snaps and routes on his way to a 72-670-6 receiving line and a third-place fantasy finish. Thomas' recovery will need to be monitored up until Week 1.

Williams signed with Arizona after spending his first four NFL seasons with the Chiefs. The 27-year-old has primarily worked as a backup/situational player, though he was busier than ever during a career-year in 2021. He finished third among backs in carries inside the 5 yard line (14) and was also top 10 in routes, receptions, receiving yards. His 19th-place finish in fantasy was his first-career top-60 campaign. Williams' career rushing efficiency is underwhelming, but he's been effective as a receiver and is in a good spot as oft-injured James Conner's potential backup (Eno Benjamin is also in the mix) in a productive offense. Standalone value is doubtful, but if Conner misses time, Williams will be a must add.

Spiller was selected by the Chargers in the fourth round of April's draft. He is a big, elusive back who contributed as both a rusher (541 carries) and receiver (99 targets) in three seasons at Texas A&M. Spiller's forced missed tackle and YAC profile was very good during his three-season run and his elusiveness really stood out in 2021 (class-best 5.0 evaded tackle rate). Spiller may need some polish in the passing game and he underwhelmed athletically at the combine, but he's also one of the youngest players in the league. The high-scoring Chargers are hunting for a "big" back complement to Austin Ekeler and 217-pound Spiller could eventually move past Sony Michel for that role. For now, he's best left on waivers.

Osborn was a pleasant surprise for Minnesota last season, emerging as a viable No. 3 wide receiver behind Justin Jefferson and Adam Thielen. The 2020 fifth-round pick went from not playing a snap as a rookie to finishing 32nd at the position in routes and 40th in fantasy points in his second season.  After hit-or-miss production in the first half of the season, Osborn's production was much better when he stepped into an every-down role in place of an injured Thielen during Weeks 13-18. Osborn scored in five of the six games and was 18th in fantasy points during the span. The 25-year-old is a good bet for more snaps in new coach Kevin O'Connell's WR-friendly offense, though he's likely to need a Jefferson or Thielen injury in order to land in the flex discussion.

Edwards is competing for work in the Baltimore backfield after missing all of 2021 with a torn ACL. Edwards became an afterthought when the Ravens selected J.K. Dobbins in the second round of the 2020 draft, but it turned out to be a mistake to overlook a young back with a career 5.2 YPC. Edwards racked up 852 yards and six TDs from scrimmage while pacing Baltimore's backfield in carries (144) and touches (153). Dobbins will be the lead man in 2022, but he's also coming off a torn ACL and isn't yet established as an NFL lead back. Once activated from the PUP list, Edwards figures to play a solid role as a rusher, but a miniscule role as a receiver (24 targets in 43 games) pushes him off the flex radar. He's best valued as insurance behind Dobbins.

Michel signed with the Chargers after spending the 2021 season with the Rams, appearing in all 21 games for the Super Bowl champs. That included a late-season six-game stretch in which he played 89% of the snaps and averaged 21.5 carries and 3.3 targets per game. Only eight backs had more fantasy points during the span. Now 27 years old, Michel is a solid back, but he's yet to post a top-30 fantasy campaign. That's unlikely to change in Los Angeles barring a major injury to Austin Ekeler, but it's possible Michel plays a big role as a rusher, leaving Ekeler to focus more on passing situations. Michel is best viewed as a deep league insurance hold, as it's possible he'd lead a committee in the event Ekeler is out.

Hamler is entering his third NFL season after his 2021 campaign was derailed by a torn ACL suffered in Week 3. The 2020 second-round pick had produced 74 yards on 10 targets prior to the injury. Hamler made some noise as a rookie (30-381-3 receiving line), but his efficiency was very poor; he ranked near the basement in catch rate (53%), YPT (6.7), YPRR (1.2) and drop rate (8.8%). Hamler is a small (5-foot-9, 178 pounds) and fast slot WR who has competition for targets with Courtland Sutton and Jerry Jeudy ahead of him on the depth chart. The arrival of Russell Wilson helps his cause, but Hamler has a tough path to consistent fantasy value. Consider the 23-year-old in the later rounds.

Foreman signed with Carolina and will compete with Chuba Hubbard for work behind feature back Christian McCaffrey. A third-round pick in 2017, Foreman did not work out in Houston, but enjoyed a career resurgence in Tennessee last season. The 233-pound bulldozer posted a 133-566-3 rushing line and was 25th among RBs in fantasy points during the nine games Derrick Henry was sidelined. Foreman is limited by a lack of receiving work (21 career targets, including 10 last season), but he has some insurance appeal considering McCaffrey's major injury woes the last two seasons. Consider the 26-year-old in the late rounds of deep leagues.

Robinson was selected by the Giants in the second round of April's draft. He is a 5-foot-8, 178-pound slot receiver who was force-fed the ball during his final season at Kentucky. In the slot 79% of the time, Robinson soaked up a class-high 40% of the Wildcats' targets, as well as 45% of the air yards. He finished first or second in this rookie class in YPRR (3.5), targets (144), receptions (104) and yards (1,334). Robinson's explosiveness and versatility (he can contribute as a rusher and returner) should lead to, at least, a gadget role in New York this season. Of course, he's a longshot for short-term fantasy value in a WR room with decent depth and will be worth no more than a late flier in 2022 drafts.

Davis signed with Baltimore after spending 2021 in Atlanta. He entered last season as the Falcons' lead back, but progressively lost his grip on the role and ended up outside the top 30 backs in touches and fantasy points despite appearing in 17 games. Davis is well below average in yards per carry (3.7), yards after contact (1.7) and yards per target (5.0) during his seven-year career and the 29-year-old is best utilized as a depth back in the pros. He may play a lot early on, but will be a long shot for fantasy value barring an injury to JK Dobbins.

Wilson signed a three-year, $22 million contract with Miami after spending his first four seasons in Dallas. The deal was a bit of an eyebrow-raiser considering Wilson was a former sixth-round pick who has been limited to a backup/situational role during his career. In fact, Wilson has 96 targets in his career, 61 of which came in 2021. In Wilson's defense, he was pretty good last season, ranking no lower than 13th among wide receivers in catch rate (74%), yards per target (9.9) and RAC (5.8). The 26-year-old aligned in the slot on 79% of his routes in Dallas and figures to see similar usage between Tyreek Hill and Jaylen Waddle in Miami. Wilson is a long shot for consistent production with Hill, Waddle and Mike Gesicki higher in priority, but he's a name to monitor in deep formats.

Perine is back with Cincinnati as the favorite for primary backup duties behind Joe Mixon. He's played that role the last two seasons, which has allowed rushing lines of 63-301-3 and 55-246-1, as well as receiving lines of 11-66-0 and 27-196-1. Perine's efficiency has been solid in recent years, but he has yet to produce a top-40 fantasy campaign in his five-year career. He can be expected to see a handful of touches each game this season and, should Mixon miss time, he'd lead a committee that would also include passing-down specialist Chris Evans. Perine is worth holding only if you roster Mixon in a very deep league.

Samuel is back for his second season in Washington after injuries limited him to 78 snaps in 2021. It was a tough break for Samuel after he progressively improved from 126th to 49th to 36th to 25th in fantasy points during his first four NFL seasons in Carolina, the latter of which included 848 yards on 76 receptions and 200 yards on 41 carries. Granted, he was oft-targeted near the line of scrimmage (7.4 aDOT), but Samuel's 79% catch rate paced all wide receivers in 2020. His durability is a concern (he's missed 23 games in five seasons) and Terry McLaurin and perhaps first-round pick Jahan Dotson will be ahead of him for targets, but he's entering his age-26 season and certainly could return to the flex discussion. Samuel deserves some late-round consideration.

Crowder signed with Buffalo after spending his first seven seasons with the Commanders and Jets. The 2015 fourth-round pick has some limitations, including a lack of work near the goal line (25 career end zone targets), a role limited to the short range (career 7.5 average depth of target) and shaky durability (at least four missed games three of the last four seasons). He's been busy when healthy, though, posting a target share of at least 17% each of the last five seasons. He has a path to a share in that range again this seaso, but he'll first need to pass Isaiah McKenzie in order to take over as team's replacement for Cole Beasley in the slot. Crowder is 29 years old and has never had a top-25 fantasy campaign, so while his ceiling is limited, Buffalo's elite, pass-heavy offense is enough to make him worth a late-round flier.

Williams signed with Atlanta and will compete with Cordarrelle Patterson and rookie Tyler Allgeier for backfield snaps. Williams was limited to 56 touches in Chicago last season and has now fallen below 75 touches in six of his seven pro seasons. He was fantasy-relevant while working in the high-scoring Kansas City offense in 2019 and theoretically has a path to a generous share of the touches in one of the league's shakiest backfields. That said, it's possible he sees enough work to flirt with occasional flex value, but especially considering he's now 30 years old, it's very likely that he'll settle in as a situational player. Williams should only be considered late in very deep leagues.
